        <body>
            <div>
                <head>Translated parts</head>
                <p xml:id="KR3f0032-start">
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0025a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-20T20:29:36.378+09:00">Commentary by Liú Huī of Wéi</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-h0021a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-20T22:19:35.074+09:00">The Nine Chapters of Arithmetics: Book I</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0032a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-27T00:30:32.588+09:00">Now presume there was a field that was 15 bù wide</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0032a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T16:53:35.783+09:00">and 16 bù long,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0032a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T17:08:18.54+09:00">[and] ask [yourself]/Question: What is the size of that field?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0033a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-21T22:08:31.562+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0033a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-21T22:08:48.681+09:00">one mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0035a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T17:10:01.32+09:00">Moreover, assume there was a field that was 12 bù wide</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0035a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T16:53:46.899+09:00">and 14 bù long,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0035a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T17:09:53.301+09:00">[and] ask [yourself]/Question: What is the size of that field?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0036a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-21T22:12:01.591+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0036a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T16:53:51.691+09:00">168 bù.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T17:16:12.453+09:00">The "rectangular field procedure" is as follows:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:07:29.981+09:00">By multiplying the number of bù for breadth and length with each other, one obtains (that results in???) the product in bù (the area in square bù). </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0049a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:26:23.676+09:00">Now presume there was a field that was one lǐ wide</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0049a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T22:36:00.745+09:00">and one lǐ long</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0049a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T22:36:08.601+09:00">[and] ask [yourself]/Question: How large is that field?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0051a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-23T20:52:29.395+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0051a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-23T21:14:10.959+09:00">Three qǐng and 75 mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0052a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:26:42.083+09:00">Moreover, presume there was a field that was 2 lǐ in breadth</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0052a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T02:24:11.356+09:00">and three lǐ in length,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0052a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:40:40.847+09:00">[and] ask [yourself]: How large is that field?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0053a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:40:42.955+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0053a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:41:22.395+09:00">22 qǐng and 50 mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:44:07.709+09:00">As for the calculation of [the size of] a field in lǐ, [it is] as follows:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:26:53.77+09:00">When you multiply the number of lǐ of the breadth and length with each other, you get the product in lǐ (i. e. the measurements of the surface in lǐ). </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:53:22.469+09:00">[And] when multiplying this by 375,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s2-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T17:53:40.027+09:00">then you get the number in mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0056a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:21:59.088+09:00">Now presume [you] had 12/18,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0056a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:27:53.14+09:00">[and] ask [yourself]/Question: If you reduced this, what would [you] get?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0057a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:12:35.936+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0057a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:12:53.282+09:00">2/3. </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0058a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:27:56.617+09:00">Moreover, presume [you] had 49/91,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0058a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:21:12.884+09:00">and ask [yourself]/Question: if you reduced this, what would [you] get?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0059a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:28:36.941+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0059a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T18:29:00.606+09:00">7/13.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:30:07.455+09:00">The reduction of fractions (Comment:)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg6a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T20:18:42.168+09:00">As for the numbers in fractions</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg7a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T20:19:11.72+09:00">when they are (overly) complex, then they are more difficult to use (work with).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T21:36:19.822+09:00">If you had 2/4</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s2-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T21:42:16.17+09:00">and you put this in a (more) complicated way</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s2-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T21:41:11.593+09:00">it could also be 4/8;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s2-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:32:35.692+09:00">[however] if you put this in a reduced way</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s2-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-10-25T21:42:44.314+09:00">then it is 1/2. </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-01T02:04:34.024+09:00">In early times, there was [a man named] Baoxi who in the beginning created eight trigrams</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T18:53:33.959+09:00">in order to illuminate the virtue of the Gods of Heaven and Earth</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s1-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T18:58:06.669+09:00">(as well as to) categorise the essential nature of all things in this world;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s1-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T19:00:31.568+09:00">he created the mathematical techniques of multiplication</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s1-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T19:58:15.172+09:00">in order to account for the changes (variations) in the six lines.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T20:15:00.275+09:00">When it came to the times of (the deity named) Huangdi, he transformed them</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T20:25:29.497+09:00">[further] developed them as he stretched them out</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T20:45:51.959+09:00">and therefore established the guidelines of the calender,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T21:13:03.826+09:00">harmonised the musical rhythms and the tones,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-02T21:36:43.278+09:00">and intended thereby to investigate the origin of the Way</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0007a-s2-seg6a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:04:22.448+09:00"/>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s4-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-27T00:39:56.714+09:00">I, Li Chunfeng, cautiously submit the following:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s4-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:08:20.33+09:00">In the book, it says that by multiplying the breadth and length with each other leads to the obtainment of the area in bù,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s4-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:08:31.961+09:00">and in the commentary, it says that [when] multiplying breadth and length with each other, you are calling [the result] a shape. </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T05:06:41.455+09:00">(This product is called the "mi" (area/shape?) of a field.)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s3-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:07:53.108+09:00">As for [the result of] the multiplication of breadth and length, it is called "mi" (area/a shape?).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s5-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-10T00:23:18.369+09:00">When you (analytically) observe the commentary's reasoning/idea</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s5-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-10T00:27:04.859+09:00">the meaning behind [the terms] "accumulation" and "shape" is the same.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s7-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:06:26.382+09:00">"Flächeninhalt" ist der Name für das Resultat, wenn sich eine Seite bzw. eine Linie einlagig entfaltet. | "Mì" is the term for a two-dimensional shape of a four-cornered surface. (CH)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s7-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:06:29.009+09:00">"Akkumulation" ist die Bezeichnung für das Resultat, wenn sich eine Zahlmenge mehrschichtig ansammelt. | "Jī" is precisely the designation for the accumulation of a set of numbers. (CH)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s6-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:09:12.388+09:00">If one applies this logic</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s7-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-17T23:29:05.311+09:00">Why is that?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s6-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:09:44.004+09:00">one would realise that this is not adequate (i.e. correct).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s8-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T04:12:25.765+09:00">When [one] insists on finding out about the concrete reference that conforms to the name/term</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s8-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T04:11:56.17+09:00">the two are entirely different.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s9-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T04:13:13.247+09:00">Even if [one] wishes to declare them to be equal,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s9-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T04:15:00.916+09:00">I, personally, am afraid that it is impossible.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s10-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:52:12.968+09:00">Now, with the word "mì" ordinarily depending on [the concept of] an area with breadth and length</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s10-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:46:16.437+09:00">the relevant word "jī" expresses all quantities of a set of bù (expresses the resulting numbers of [a product in] bù).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s11-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:47:12.94+09:00">When it says in the book that when multiplying [two numbers] with each other one obtains the product in bù,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s11-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:51:29.12+09:00">then that is [the rule] stated for the aforementioned quantities.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s12-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:52:09.386+09:00">When it says in the commentary that this is identical to [the meaning of] "mì"</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s12-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T16:53:58.959+09:00">then that completely goes against the basic meaning of/understanding behind the "product in bù".</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s13-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:03:18.264+09:00">The previously mentioned [concept of the] product being [identical with] the area/surface of a field in this commentary</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s13-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:02:56.94+09:00">depends on logically obtaining a full understanding (of this).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s14-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:05:06.192+09:00">Repeatedly stating that it is identical to "mì"</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s14-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:06:14.381+09:00">is (needlessly) complicated and incorrect.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s15-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:09:12.682+09:00">Now, for the elucidation of the commentary</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s16-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:30:17.423+09:00">The method in order to [find out the] mǔ is to divide by 240 bù</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s16-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:30:55.098+09:00">and thereupon one receives the number of mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s17-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:31:20.216+09:00">100 mǔ is one qǐng.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s18-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-27T00:41:21.739+09:00">I, Li Chunfeng, cautiously submit the following:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s18-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:34:19.368+09:00">This being the end of the volume</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s18-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:50:42.128+09:00">there are generally two individual ways of expressing qǐng and mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s15-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:54:57.15+09:00">as well as preserve it all for future study.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s15-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:53:09.909+09:00">[it is meant to] preserve the rights and remove the wrongs</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s15-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T17:54:45.234+09:00">and [to provide] a summary that is useful and simple</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s19-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T18:21:35.981+09:00">The remaining methods are not touched upon again,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s19-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T18:21:45.429+09:00">and therefore cannot be determined (known).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-21T18:48:31.476+09:00">Comment:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:09:12.868+09:00">a field of one mǔ</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:13:35.494+09:00">with the breadth of 15 bù:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:15:04.672+09:00">creating 15 rows;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg6a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:12:17.648+09:00">then every row's breadth is one bù and [their] length is 16 bù.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s20-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:12:03.14+09:00">if one divides it length-wise</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s21-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:43:49.346+09:00">Moreover, if you cut (the length) of (one) side</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s21-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:44:02.842+09:00">that would cause it to be 16 rows</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s21-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:12:25.28+09:00">and then each row's breadth would be one bù and (its) length would be 15 bù.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s22-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:45:04.084+09:00">each of them is in itself a four-cornered shape.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s23-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:47:27.603+09:00">When all of them have (a surface area of) 240 bù</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s23-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:48:43.703+09:00">they cover an area of one mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s23-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:51:03.206+09:00">The amount of bù [should be] the exact same.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s24-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:50:29.764+09:00">By that one can deduce (say)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s24-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:12:47.919+09:00">that by multiplying breadth with length, one obtains the product in bù.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s24-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:52:30.396+09:00">This has been proven.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s25-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-23T22:52:44.725+09:00">240 bù</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s25-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:13:16.151+09:00">is the divisor for mǔ;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s25-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:13:27.272+09:00">100 mǔ</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s25-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:14:24.643+09:00">is the divisor for qǐng.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s26-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:14:38.029+09:00">That is why by dividing them</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0038a-s26-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:23:11.279+09:00">you then receive (each new unit).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s3-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:23:43.483+09:00">Comment:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s3-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:27:05.768+09:00">In this exercise, multiplying the number of lǐ of [both] breadth and length leads to obtaining the product in lǐ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s4-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:25:39.559+09:00">In a field of [one?] lǐ there are 3 qǐng and 75 mǔ,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s4-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:26:08.477+09:00">so by multiplying these [accordingly]</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0054a-s4-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:26:20.579+09:00">you then receive the number in mǔ.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T17:30:12.003+09:00">As for the reduction of fractions,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-11-24T00:30:44.319+09:00">the quantities in these kinds of things</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-06T16:31:29.199+09:00">they do not have to be (are not necessarily) whole numbers</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s1-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T16:05:38.462+09:00">and one must certainly state the following about them:</seg>
                <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s3-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T16:16:06.081+09:00">Even if you then have different formulations (of the same thing)</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s3-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T16:21:04.54+09:00">what you arrive at is a number/quantity</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s3-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-01T16:23:51.061+09:00">it will surely go back to the same original state (and that is it).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2022-12-03T22:05:43.488+09:00">The procedure (for simplifying/reducing parts) [is as follows:]</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-07T00:29:51.687+09:00">if they can be halved, halve them;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-07T00:29:55.787+09:00">if they cannot be halved:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2022-12-07T00:31:02.313+09:00">on the side lay down the [counting rods corresponding to the] numerical values of the fraction's numerator and denominator</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg5a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2022-12-07T00:40:59.059+09:00">take the lesser, subtract [it] from the greater,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg6a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2022-12-11T04:57:21.317+09:00">repeatedly subtracting the one from the other reduces [the greater],</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s5-seg7a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-14T18:46:20.214+09:00">seeking their equality (equality of their values).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0060a-s6-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2022-12-07T00:57:30.703+09:00">Take [that] equal number and simplify them [the denominator and the numerator].</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s9-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:28:05.807+09:00">"1"</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s9-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:38:40.182+09:00">refers to reducing it (the quantity specified above?) by 5</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s9-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:37:01.193+09:00">causing each 5 to be (become?) 1.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s10-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:32:10.366+09:00">Once that is done,</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s10-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:32:46.433+09:00">it (the result of that division) is then multiplied by 3</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s10-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:36:55.327+09:00">causing each 1 to be (become?) 3.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s11-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:54:32.164+09:00">In this way</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0279a-s11-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-15T17:54:40.539+09:00">all lü ultimately go back to/refer to the unit.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s8-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:17:40.593+09:00">Whenever numbers are associated with each other (that means numbers are reduced or magnified simultaneously by the same proportion), one calls them the terms of a ratio.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s9-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-22T17:37:46.991+09:00">The terms of a ratio</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s9-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-22T17:47:10.842+09:00">because they are in and of itself associated with each other, they interact.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s10-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2022-12-22T17:48:12.145+09:00">If there are fractions then (the whole integer parts) can be scattered (into fractions).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s10-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:01:43.341+09:00">If a fraction has overlapping parts (common divisors) [in its numerator and its denominator], then simplify [it]/(that fraction).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0621a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:41:13.44+09:00">Now presume one lends 1,000 cash to someone</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0621a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:42:06.55+09:00">and the monthly interest is 30 (cash).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0621a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:42:35.805+09:00">Now presume one lends 750 cash to someone</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0621a-s2-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:44:17.833+09:00">and after nine days they return it;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0621a-s2-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:45:30.333+09:00">question: how much interest [does that amount to]?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0622a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:45:36.419+09:00">Answer:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0622a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:46:02.163+09:00">[It amounts to] 6 3/4 cash.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s1-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-13T17:06:40.142+09:00">The procedure is [as follows]:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s1-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:49:07.14+09:00">Take the 30 days in a month multiplied by 1,000 cash as the divisor.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s2-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:49:49.936+09:00">Taking the 30 days multiplied by 1,000 cash as the divisor:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s2-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:59:49.609+09:00">one obtains 30,000</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s2-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:00:00.258+09:00">which is like lending someone 30,000 cash</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s2-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T16:57:57.98+09:00">at a daily interest of 30.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s3-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-13T17:08:46.09+09:00">Take the interest of 30 and multiply by the presumed amount of cash lent.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s3-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-13T17:08:49.154+09:00">Moreover multiply that [result] by 9 days</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s3-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:14:21.52+09:00">and set that as the dividend.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s4-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:23:14.675+09:00">By dividing, one obtains the units of cash.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s5-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:47:05.314+09:00">Consider the 9 days multiplied by the presumed amount of cash lent as the given amount of cash presumed for one day;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s5-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:47:17.193+09:00">in the procedure of "Let Us Presume" this is the "Given Amount".</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s5-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:48:49.806+09:00">The interest of 30 is the "Lü Of What Is Sought"</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s5-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-12T17:49:14.056+09:00">and the 30,000 cash are the "Lü Of What Is Given".</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s6-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-02T17:58:27.484+09:00">As an alternative to this, one could divide the interest of 30 cash with the 30 days in a month;</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s6-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-19T17:53:27.964+09:00">this makes 10 fēn (= 1 cash) per day.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p1104a-s9-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-01-26T20:43:47.422+09:00"/>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s6-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2023-02-02T08:35:48.441+09:00">*Multiply the given amount of cash presumed for one day with it and take [the result] as the dividend.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s6-seg4a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-02T17:14:41.528+09:00">Take 1000 cash as divisor.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s7-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-02T17:47:39.641+09:00">As for the working on the lü, </seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s7-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-02T17:48:11.256+09:00">one does that by making them correspond to 'one' (day).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s8-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2023-02-02T08:29:18.464+09:00">Therefore, by the 30 days, one can either multiply the original [amount of cash]</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s8-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#andrea.breard" modified="2023-02-02T08:27:12.864+09:00">or one can divide the interest.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0623a-s8-seg3a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-02T17:49:46.872+09:00">In either case, it is a way to make them (the lü) correspond (to one day).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s11-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:09:11.661+09:00">[The reason why] one divides the dividend and the divisor by the same number</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s11-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:46:09.525+09:00">is that they are associated terms of a ratio.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s12-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:46:51.876+09:00">Therefore when it comes to the scattering of parts</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s12-seg2a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:45:38.197+09:00">multiplying both denominators with each other, without fail, determines the divisor and the dividend.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR3f0032_tls_001-p0107a-s13-seg1a" xml:lang="en" resp="#Valerie.Kiel" modified="2023-02-09T17:45:35.523+09:00"/>
                </p>
            </div>
